r"""
state_size patch for simple_sim_cont_time_gruode.py
===================================================

SYMPTOM
    ValueError: X has 6 features, but StandardScaler is expecting 5 features
    at  y0_seed = NEXT_scalar.transform(np.asarray([y0_phys]))[0]

ROOT CAUSE
    NEXT_extrapolation() sets the physical-state width as:

        state_size = 6
        if use_grdth:
            state_size = 5

    i.e. it only knows GRDTH is 5-state. But your model is GEODESIC-INTEGRATED,
    which is ALSO 5-state -- the "frame trick" drops absolute azimuth and tracks
    azimuth rate: [s, h, v_s, v_alpha, v_h]. (NEXT_training sets model_states=5
    for frame=="geodesic" and geodesic_mode=="integrated".) The sim defaulted to
    6, so it sliced a 6-vector and the 5-feature scaler rejected it.

    The export script already confirmed the true width: it derived
    model_states=5 straight from the checkpoint tensors.

FIX (two options -- OPTION A recommended)
    OPTION A -- derive state_size from the ENCODER graph the sim already loads.
    The encoder input width IS the model's physical-state dimension, so this is
    authoritative for ANY model and needs no per-frame special-casing.

    OPTION B -- if you'd rather keep it explicit, just teach the existing
    branch that geodesic-integrated is 5-state.

Both are shown below. They edit only NEXT_extrapolation() in
simple_sim_cont_time_gruode.py.
"""

